‚óŹ I read the wisp config and the help-session findings (rounds 1‚Äď6 from earlier
  today). Important context: prior rounds concluded mt7925_common was the
  producer under a graphical session, but your new TTY-only PASS/FAIL table
  contradicts that ‚ÄĒ with WiFi modules loaded throughout, the only thing that
  flips clean ‚ÜĒ crash is amdgpu. So this is either a different bug only
  exercised in the TTY/fbcon path, or the previous attribution missed something.
   We need fresh evidence.

  You already have panic_on_warn=1, softlockup_panic=1, panic_on_rcu_stall=1,
  and slub_debug=FZP on, so a hang or WARN should leave a pstore dump and a
  kernel oops in the previous-boot journal. Run the commands below and paste the
   output.

  1. Confirm what just booted (so we can tell which test config crashed)

  cat /proc/cmdline
  uname -a
  sudo dmidecode -s bios-version; sudo dmidecode -s system-product-name

  2. Did pstore capture the crash?

  sudo ls -lat /var/lib/systemd/pstore/ 2>/dev/null | head -20
  sudo ls -lat /sys/fs/pstore/ 2>/dev/null | head -20
  If there is a fresh dir in /var/lib/systemd/pstore/, dump it whole ‚ÄĒ that's
  the gold:
  NEWEST=$(sudo ls -t /var/lib/systemd/pstore/ | head -1); echo "=== $NEWEST
  ==="; sudo ls -la /var/lib/systemd/pstore/"$NEWEST"; sudo cat
  /var/lib/systemd/pstore/"$NEWEST"/dmesg.txt 2>/dev/null

  3. Previous-boot kernel log ‚ÄĒ the part right before the crash matters most

  sudo journalctl -k -b -1 --no-pager | tail -400
  Plus a filtered view that surfaces oops / WARN / DRM / amdgpu-specific bits:
  sudo journalctl -k -b -1 --no-pager | grep -iE 'amdgpu|drm|amd_pmf|smu|psp|gpu
   reset|ring|fence|ib test|warn|bug:|oops|panic|stall|softlockup|call
  trace|rip:|page fault|gpf|null pointer' | tail -200

  4. Full unredacted previous-boot journal (so we can grep ourselves)

  This is the most important single artifact ‚ÄĒ the watchdog-panic params should
  have produced a multi-CPU dump in here:
  sudo journalctl -k -b -1 --no-pager > /tmp/wisp-prevboot.log
  wc -l /tmp/wisp-prevboot.log
  Save /tmp/wisp-prevboot.log into the next help-session dir as
  oops-2026-04-29T<HHMM>Z.txt, or paste the last ~800 lines.

  5. State of the suspect drivers on the current boot

  This tells us what was loaded at the moment of the crash, since the current
  boot started with the same blacklist (or absence of one) you're testing:
  lsmod | grep -E '^(amdgpu|amdxdna|amd_pmf|amd_isp4|pinctrl_amdisp|i2c_designwa
  re_amdisp|mt7925e|mt7925_common|mt76)'
  ls /sys/module/amdgpu/drivers/ 2>/dev/null
  lspci -nnk | grep -A3 -iE 'vga|3d|display|network|wireless'

  6. amdgpu firmware load ‚ÄĒ Strix Halo is new silicon and missing/old fw is a 
