‚óŹ The pstore dump rules out amdgpu. The panic is in the WiFi runtime-PM path:

  WARNING: net/core/netmem_priv.h:18 at page_pool_clear_pp_info+0x39/0x40
  Workqueue: mt76 mt792x_pm_wake_work [mt792x_lib]
   page_pool_clear_pp_info
   page_pool_return_netmem
   mt76_dma_rx_cleanup [mt76]
   mt792x_wpdma_reset [mt792x_lib]
   mt792x_wpdma_reinit_cond [mt792x_lib]
   mt792xe_mcu_drv_pmctrl [mt792x_lib]
   mt792x_mcu_drv_pmctrl [mt792x_lib]
   mt792x_pm_wake_work [mt792x_lib]

  panic_on_warn=1 tripped a pp_magic check while mt76_dma_rx_cleanup was
  returning RX netmems to the page pool from the WiFi chip's runtime-PM wake
  handler. Same mt76/mt7925 family the round-2 and round-3 slub_debug receipts
  pointed at (skbuff_small_head / anon_vma_chain 16-byte pointer-shaped writes).
   The crash hit at uptime 312s ‚ÄĒ the "‚Čą5 min" you observed.

  The amdgpu PASS/FAIL pattern was a red herring. The path that fires the bug is
   mt792x_pm_wake_work, which runs after the WiFi chip has been idle long enough
   to enter MCU power-save and then needs to be woken. TTY vs. desktop probably
  changes the idle-vs-busy pattern of the WiFi link enough to gate how often
  that wake cycle fires, which made it look like amdgpu was the variable. The
  producer is mt76.

  Mitigation

  Re-apply your round-7 plan ‚ÄĒ blacklist the mt7925 pair. Edit
  hosts/wisp/configuration.nix:

  "module_blacklist=mt7925e,mt7925_common"

  (uncomment that one line; leave the others commented). Then sudo nixos-rebuild
   switch --flake .#wisp && sudo reboot. WiFi/BT will be off ‚ÄĒ use ethernet via
  the dock, a phone hotspot, or a USB WiFi dongle. Soak the TTY case ‚Č•30 min to
  confirm the 5-minute crash is gone.

