‚ĚĮ I'm not convinced amdgpu is unrelated. I tried SEVERAL times, and EVERY time  
  I booted with amdgpu, the system would crash. And it never crashed without    
  amdgpu (in the last few hours of testing).                                    
                                                                                
  I'm not denying the culprit is the mediatek driver, but perhpas it only       
  misbehaves when the gpu driver is enabled, e.g. perhaps an electrical         
  power/noise issue.                                                            

‚óŹ You're right ‚ÄĒ I was dismissing your data. Both things can be true: the
  corrupted-state-and-WARN happens inside mt76, but it only happens when
  amdgpu's presence changes the system's power-management behavior enough to
  make mt792x_pm_wake_work actually fire. That fits everything we have:

  - The oops is in the WiFi MCU wake handler. That handler only runs after the
  chip has entered MCU power-save and needs to be woken. With amdgpu off, the
  WiFi chip likely never enters that low-power state at all, so the buggy
  wake/DMA-reset path is never executed and no WARN fires.
  - amdgpu pulls in amd_pmf and the SMU and changes ASPM/D-state policy across
  the SoC. On Strix Halo the iGPU, NPU, and WiFi share the PCIe fabric and SMU ‚ÄĒ
   a power-policy change on one side moves the others.
  - Your dmesg even reports amdgpu 0000:c3:00.0: amdgpu: Runtime PM not 
  available ‚ÄĒ so it's not amdgpu's own runtime PM, but it's still influencing
  the platform PM state that gates the WiFi chip's MCU sleep.
  - TTY vs. Wayland would matter for exactly this reason: a quiet TTY hits
  deeper idle, the WiFi chip sleeps longer/more often, the wake path runs more
  often.

  Electrical/noise coupling is possible but harder to test, so let's hold that
  hypothesis and try the cheaper one first: stop the WiFi chip from entering MCU
   power-save (or stop the PCIe link from changing state) while keeping both
  drivers loaded.

  Proposed test order ‚ÄĒ cheap ‚Üí invasive

  Test A: pin the WiFi PCIe device to D0 (most surgical). This blocks the exact
  wake path that crashed without touching amdgpu, ASPM, or anything else.

  In hosts/wisp/configuration.nix, add a tmpfiles rule that writes on to the
  WiFi PCIe device's power/control at boot:

  systemd.tmpfiles.rules = [
    "w /sys/bus/pci/devices/0000:c1:00.0/power/control - - - - on"
  ];

  Plus a udev rule so it sticks if the device re-enumerates:

  services.udev.extraRules = ''
    ACTION=="add", SUBSYSTEM=="pci", KERNEL=="0000:c1:00.0", 
  ATTR{power/control}="on"
  '';

  Leave module_blacklist= empty, leave amdgpu loaded, soak in TTY ‚Č•30 min.

  - Clean: confirms it's the runtime-PM wake path. WiFi stays usable. We can
  also report this upstream as a clean repro recipe.
  - Crash: path-pinning didn't catch it; move to test B.

  Test B: disable PCIe ASPM globally ‚ÄĒ pcie_aspm=off in boot.kernelParams. Same
  soak. This forces all PCIe links to L0 and rules out link-state transitions (a
   common couplant for "GPU loaded, WiFi misbehaves" bugs).

  Test C: pin amdgpu to high performance ‚ÄĒ
  power_dpm_force_performance_level=high via tmpfiles. Tests whether GPU DPM
  transitions, not link transitions, are the trigger. (Currently auto.)

  Tests A/B/C are all cheap, single-knob, fully reversible, and keep WiFi/BT
  working. If A is clean we have a real fix that doesn't sacrifice WiFi.

  About the upstream report

  If A or B is clean, the report becomes much sharper: "mt76 mt792x_pm_wake_work
   corrupts page-pool state on MT7925 when the chip is allowed to enter MCU
  power-save, observable on AMD Strix Halo with amdgpu loaded; pinning the
  device to D0 (or pcie_aspm=off) avoids the path." That's a much more useful
  bug report than a blanket "blacklist the driver" workaround.

  Want me to make the test-A edit (tmpfiles + udev rule) on the current branch
  and update hosts/wisp/configuration.nix's comment block to record this refined
   hypothesis?

